Hi friends =F0=9F=91=8B,
Happy Friday and welcome to our 22nd Weekly Dose of Optimism. After taking =
off last Friday for Thanksgiving, we=E2=80=99re back at it with a big ole=
=E2=80=99 dose of optimism this week.
Let=E2=80=99s get to it.
The Weekly Dose is brought to you by=E2=80=A6 Oceans [ https://substack.com=
/redirect/76d6f836-4004-4349-803e-836f5f99273c?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5=
T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Oceans is a white glove outsourcing firm purpose built to help=C2=A0small b=
usinesses, busy executives, and high growth companies easily find and work =
with the best global talent in operational roles. All Oceans talent comes f=
rom Sri Lanka.=20
Why Sri Lanka? Simple: it has the best talent-to-price ratio on the planet.=
 Oceans [ https://substack.com/redirect/76d6f836-4004-4349-803e-836f5f99273=
c?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] recr=
uits, vets, trains, and employs top talent in the region from name brand fi=
rms and universities. You pay between $2,500 - $3,500 per month for a full =
time, embedded team member with 5-10 years of experience. That=E2=80=99s ~$=
36K/yr for talent that would cost $150K+ (easily) in the US.
They are already serving clients like Austin Reif (Morning Brew), Ndamukong=
 Suh (Philadelphia Eagles), Joe McCann (Asymmetric Financial) and dozens of=
 high growth SMBs. So if you=E2=80=99re looking top, affordable talent to t=
ake on operational roles (EA+, Operations, Sales/Marketing, Finance, Backof=
fice), check out Oceans [ https://substack.com/redirect/76d6f836-4004-4349-=
803e-836f5f99273c?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6=
m8ExkRNpU ].
(1) Experimental drug appears to slow progression of Alzheimer=E2=80=99s di=
sease in clinical trial but raises safety concerns [ https://substack.com/r=
edirect/66ccc26d-ab5f-45a4-973d-4bb1c9771823?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7=
GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Jacqueline Howard [ https://substack.com/redirect/af9f0d10-3609-4b62-8680-7=
6c31538304c?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkR=
NpU ] for CNN.com
=E2=80=9CIn persons with early Alzheimer=E2=80=99s disease, lecanemab reduc=
ed brain amyloid levels and was associated with less decline on clinical me=
asures of cognition and function than placebo at 18 months but was associat=
ed with adverse events,=E2=80=9D the researchers wrote. =E2=80=9CLonger tri=
als are warranted to determine the efficacy and safety of lecanemab in earl=
y Alzheimer=E2=80=99s disease.=E2=80=9D
The Alzheimer=E2=80=99s Association said in a statement Tuesday that it wel=
comes and is further encouraged by the full Phase 3 data.
Alzheimer=E2=80=99s disease hits close to home for many people, including t=
he McCormicks. About 10% of the US population older than 65 suffers from Al=
zheimer=E2=80=99s. Our maternal grandmother had it, which means that our mo=
ther and her children are at higher risk of developing it. It=E2=80=99s som=
ething we think about a lot and it=E2=80=99s pretty darn scary. Which is wh=
y promising Alzheimer=E2=80=99s treatment news, like the story above, is so=
 exciting to us. (And it=E2=80=99s also why stories like this [ https://sub=
stack.com/redirect/b783c9b5-4c2d-4f79-8523-00df2a46e9c5?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3Q=
ifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], in which researchers fab=
ricated data that set back other research many years, is so frustrating.)
According to new Phase 3 Trial results [ https://substack.com/redirect/8c15=
7329-5f35-4b79-ad44-100aba2c149b?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZj=
mlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], published in the New England Journal of Medicin=
e, the experimental drug lecanemab had been found to reduce cognitive and f=
unctional decline by 27% at month 18. While more data and longer trials (fo=
r example, Phase 2 Trials showed no significant improvement at month 12) ar=
e needed =E2=80=94 this is a promising sign that the treatment may at least=
 slow the horrendous symptoms of Alzheimer=E2=80=99s, giving back valuable =
time to patients and their loved ones.
(2) Generative AI: autocomplete for everything [ https://substack.com/redir=
ect/1e62d78f-177a-4992-a65c-09a71d8ed4a9?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_=
ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Noah Smith [ https://substack.com/redirect/4c8a7cd2-863b-448c-ab70-3cede905=
2750?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] a=
nd roon [ https://substack.com/redirect/3ea1f037-b214-46b1-9bdf-3ff6f2bf975=
2?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] for =
Noahpinion
In an era when much of the tech industry seems to be down in the dumps, AI =
is experiencing a golden age. And this has lots of people worried.
To put it bluntly, we think the fear, and the guilt, are probably mostly un=
warranted. No one knows, of course, but we suspect that AI is far more like=
ly to complement and empower human workers than to impoverish them or displ=
ace them onto the welfare rolls. This doesn=E2=80=99t mean we=E2=80=99re st=
arry-eyed Panglossians; we realize that this optimistic perspective is a to=
ugh sell, and even if our vision comes true, there will certainly be some p=
eople who lose out. But what we=E2=80=99ve seen so far about how generative=
 AI works suggests that it=E2=80=99ll largely behave like the productivity-=
enhancing, labor-saving tools of past waves of innovation.
We=E2=80=99ve got shape rotators and wordcels teaming up to explain why gen=
erative AI is not going to steal all of the jobs =E2=80=94 this is peak tec=
h twitter! Their argument is both optimistic and convincing. Generative AI,=
 they claim, will just be another tool that enhances creativity and frees u=
p humans to work on higher-level tasks. It is less a job killer and more a =
job augmenter. Will generative AI one day replace Packy at Not Boring? Mayb=
e. Will Packy use generative AI to make his work better or complete his wor=
k more quickly? Definitely.
But not everyone is a newsletter writer (thankfully there are non-wordcels =
out there) =E2=80=94 are their jobs more at risk or are their jobs less lik=
ely to benefit from generative AI? Tough to say at this point. Some industr=
ies will be up-ended and others will barely be impacted, but our belief is =
that in aggregate, generative AI will increase productivity and, at worst, =
be a positive force of creative destruction.
(3) chat.openai.com [ https://substack.com/redirect/214f9d18-ac87-4038-9d2f=
-f9a092bc6083?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8Ex=
kRNpU ]
Speaking of generative AI, OpenAI launched ChatGPT and it is uh pretty insa=
ne. ChatGPT was trained to interact in a conversational way, and the dialog=
ue format allows it to =E2=80=9Canswer follow-up questions, admit mistakes,=
 challenge incorrect premises, and reject inappropriate requests.=E2=80=9D =
It=E2=80=99s pretty similar to GPT-3, but with an easier user experience th=
at you could easily imagine working into your daily life. Packy had ChatGPT=
 basically build a Ben Tossell [ https://substack.com/redirect/9253bd22-453=
5-458f-b52e-36a1fc78db6d?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKb=
qOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] has a full thread [ https://substack.com/redirect/6dcb2c=
71-e90b-4014-b1b3-31dc1d0296b2?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjml=
XXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] on early use cases and their implications but to h=
ighlight a few:
Debugging code=E2=80=A6and explaining the fix [ https://substack.com/redire=
ct/08d6bd44-e138-4fc0-8af9-e8adcb6d3b88?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_Z=
lNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Providing better search results than Google [ https://substack.com/redirect=
/e710ff90-d6ca-418f-9b8f-08728cb414e8?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlN=
uaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Writing a Seinfield episode [ https://substack.com/redirect/67dd39b7-6c45-4=
986-8634-f90f8e74fdae?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOs=
a8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Google has about as deep of moats as any analysts could dream of, but if th=
ere ever was a Google-killer out there, we imagine that it'd start out look=
ing something like ChatGPT.
(4) AI Learns the Art of Diplomacy [ https://substack.com/redirect/c4cf04cf=
-1b42-4669-8f4b-a22076d13b77?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXX=
epKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Matthew Huston [ https://substack.com/redirect/9384189a-41d8-40c6-b1d4-3658=
0d98bf1b?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU=
 ] for Science
OK, we promise this is the last AI story this week. Meta has developed an A=
I that can beat humans in the board game Diplomacy. The game, which require=
s a combination of strategic planning, persuasion, intuition and verbal neg=
otiation was thought to be off-limits for even the most powerful of AIs. Bu=
t CICERO, the AI model created by Meta, developed the strategic and tactica=
l capabilities necessary to out maneuver humans after being trained on over=
 125,000 online Diplomacy games. CICERO then played 40 online games, and pl=
aced in the top 10% of players.
Of course, like real life diplomats, skillful players of Diplomacy need to =
be able to manipulate, coerce and extract information from other agents, wh=
ich opens up a whole can of worms as to whether or not Meta should have con=
trol of an algorithm that powerful. For now, though, we=E2=80=99ll classify=
 this under another seemingly important accomplishment in AI research.
(5) Physicists Create =E2=80=98the Smallest, Crummiest Wormhole You Can Ima=
gine=E2=80=99 [ https://substack.com/redirect/f3b976b5-9cbe-426f-8243-2ffb9=
800cfe6?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU =
]
Dennis Overbye [ https://substack.com/redirect/0c40daa0-1e34-4490-bc20-aefa=
821cf62c?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU=
 ] for The New York Times
In an experiment that ticks most of the mystery boxes in modern physics, a =
group of researchers announced on Wednesday that they had simulated a pair =
of black holes in a quantum computer and sent a message between them throug=
h a shortcut in space-time called a wormhole. Physicists described the achi=
evement as another small step in the effort to understand the relation betw=
een gravity, which shapes the universe, and quantum mechanics, which govern=
s the subatomic realm of particles.
Are we in the trust tree? Good. I=E2=80=99m going to be honest here: I have=
 no idea what these researchers actually pulled off, but it seems interesti=
ng and potentially(?) important. Here=E2=80=99s my layman=E2=80=99s summary=
: a team of researchers developed a computational simulation of a wormhole =
that gives them a better model from which to study and understand the chara=
cteristics of actual wormholes. If you read the article, you=E2=80=99ll fin=
d that other physicists are skeptical of the research=E2=80=99s importance,=
 with one MIT physicists quipping, =E2=80=9CIt is exciting as a technical a=
chievement, because if we can=E2=80=99t even do this (and until now we coul=
dn=E2=80=99t), then simulating more interesting quantum gravity theories wo=
uld CERTAINLY be off the table.=E2=80=9D
Saltiness aside, it is important to note that almost all research on wormho=
les is, at this time, theoretical. While the general theory of relativity p=
redicts wormholes, these bridges through space-time remain hypothetical.
BONUS: Chose Good Quests [ https://substack.com/redirect/89e444c7-0590-4c5a=
-9d4e-67ce7d532f21?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-=
6m8ExkRNpU ]
Trae Stephens [ https://substack.com/redirect/cb3f7ee1-a79c-48ad-a69d-0dd37=
6d16c49?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU =
] and Markie Wagner [ https://substack.com/redirect/4a949007-34e1-49a1-8f06=
-88e307ccc181?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8Ex=
kRNpU ] for Pirate Wires
In the most simple terms possible: a good quest makes the future better tha=
n our world today, while a bad quest doesn't improve the world much at all,=
 or even makes it worse. Today, we are in a crisis. Silicon Valley's best =
=E2=80=94 our top operators, exited founders, and most powerful investors =
=E2=80=94 are almost all on bad quests.
Trae Stephens of Anduril and Founders Fund and Markie Wagner of Delphi Labs=
 argue that there is a moral imperative for Silicon Valley=E2=80=99s best a=
nd brightest to pursue, what they call, =E2=80=9CGood Quests.=E2=80=9D A go=
od quest is both operationally hard and consequential. Think colonizing Mar=
s, developing AGI, curing cancer, etc. The essay, in a way, is a response t=
o the famous quote from Facebook engineer Jeff Hammerbacher, =E2=80=9CThe b=
est minds of my generation are thinking about how to make people click ads.=
=E2=80=9D It=E2=80=99s a call to action for our best operators to start wor=
king on meaningful, complex, and important work, and emblematic of the type=
 of optimism we celebrate at Not Boring.
That=E2=80=99s all for this week. If you enjoyed this week=E2=80=99s email,=
 please share it with a friend or two!
I=E2=80=99ll be back in your inbox 9am EST on Monday morning. Enjoy the wee=
kend.
Packy

